<section xml:id="s_quotient_group" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Quotient groups</title>

    <p>
        Given a subgroup <m>H</m> of <m>G</m> we would like to put a group structure on the coset space <m>G/H</m>: indeed, what could be more natural than to define our binary operation as 
        <men xml:id="eq_coset_law_prop">
            gH\cdot g'H=(gg')H
        </men>?
    It would seem the relevant group operations would follow readily from this definition. The issue is that the proposed operation is not always well defined! That is, if <m>gH=g'H</m> and <m>kH=k'H</m> for elements <m>g,g',k,k'\in G</m>, it is not necessarily the case that <m>(gk)H=(g'h')H</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
        Indeed, continuing with <xref ref="eg_cosets_Dn"/>, where <m>G=D_4</m> and <m>H=\angvec{rs}</m>, we have 
        <md>
            <mrow>rH \amp =(r^2s)H\amp  </mrow>
            <mrow> r^3H \amp =sH</mrow>
        </md>
        and yet 
        <md>
            <mrow>(rr^3)H \amp =H \amp 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>((r^2s)s)H\amp =r^2H\ne H</mrow>
        </md>.
    It turns out that magic property a subgroup <m>H</m> needs to satisfy in order for the operation <xref ref="eq_coset_law_prop"/> to be well defined is that <m>H</m> be a <em>normal subgroup</em>.  
    </p>
    
    <definition xml:id="d_normal_subgroup">
    <title>Normal subgroup</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    A subgroup <m>N</m> of the group <m>G</m> is called <term>normal</term> if 
    <md>
        <mrow>gNg^{-1} \amp = N </mrow>
    </md>
    for all <m>g\in G</m>. We write <m>N\normalin G</m> to indicate that <m>N</m> is a normal subgroup of <m>G</m>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <theorem xml:id="th_normal">
    <title>Normal subgroups</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>N</m> be a subgroup of the group <m>G</m>. The following statements are equivalent. 
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>N\normalin G</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>N_G(N)=G</m>
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>gN=Ng</m> for all <m>g\in G</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        
        <li>
            <p>
                The operation 
                <md>
                    <mrow>G/N \times G/N\amp \rightarrow G/N</mrow>
                    <mrow>(gN, hN) \amp \longmapsto (gh)N</mrow>
                </md>
                is well defined. 
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
    <p>
        The equivalence <m>(1)\iff (2)</m> follows directly from the definition of normality and <m>N_G(N)</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
        The equivalence <m>(1)\iff (3)</m> is left as an exercise. 
    </p>
    <p>
        We prove <m>(3)\implies (4)</m>. Assume <m>gN=Ng</m>. Assume <m>gN=g'N</m> and <m>hN=h'N</m>. We will show that 
        <me>
            (gh)N=(g'h')N
        </me>.
         Since <m>gN=g'N</m> and <m>hN=h'N</m>, we have <m>g=g'n</m> and <m>h=h'n'</m> for some elements <m>n,n'\in N</m>, and thus 
        <me>
            gh=g'nh'n'
        </me>.
        Next since <m>hN=Nh</m> (assuming (3)), we have <m>nh'=h'n''</m> for some <m>n''\in N</m>, yielding 
        <me>
            gh=g'h'n'' n'\in (g'h')N
        </me>.
        It follows from <xref ref="th_cosets"/> that <m>(gh)N=(g'h')N</m>, as desired.
    </p>
    <p>
        The implication <m>(4)\implies (3)</m> is left as an exercise. 
    </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>
    <theorem xml:id="th_quot_group">
    <title>Quotient groups</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>N</m> be a normal subgroup of the group <m>G</m>. 
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
            The pair <m>(G/N, \cdot)</m>, where <m>\cdot</m> is the operation
    <md>
        <mrow>G/N\times G/N \amp \rightarrow G/N</mrow>
        <mrow>(gN, g'N) \amp \rightarrow gN\cdot g'N=(gg')N </mrow>
    </md>,
    is a group.
    </p>
    <p>
        The group identity of <m>G/N</m> is the coset <m>N</m>. Given coset <m>gN\in G/N</m> its group inverse is the coset <m>g^{-1}N</m>.
    </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                The map <m>\pi\colon G\rightarrow G/N</m> defined as <m>\pi(g)=gN</m> is a surjective group homormorphism satisfying <m>\ker\pi=N</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
</p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
    <p>
    </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>
